\begin_layout Standard
The results are in clear agreement with the theory and are statisticly significa
nt.
 However, there is still a glaring problem which has not been addressed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a discrepancy between the fit line and number of events at the
 lower range of the mass spectrum.
 A possible cause for this discrepancy is our method of measurement, specificall
y how the angle between the photons is measured.
 The method requires 2 distinct pulse-height clusters, which means the sum
 of the showers' widths must be smaller than the distance between them.
 For a suffieciently energetic particle or a small enough angle, 2 clusters
 are impossible.
 This, in turn, means that below a certain angle measurements are much more
 likely to be discarded.
 Noting the fact that the invariant mass squared is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\cos\theta$
\end_inset

, it is clear why our measurements are lacking in events with a small invariant
 mass.
 Future pairs attempting to recreate our experiment should check, using
 the tools provided (Link to code), which momentum, after filtering, gives
 the most satisfactory histogram.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Measurements concerning 
\begin_inset Formula $\k$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The meson 
\begin_inset Formula $\k$
\end_inset

 is made up of 
\begin_inset Formula $d\,\bar{s}$
\end_inset

 pair.
 Its invariant mass is 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{PDG}^{\k}=4.97611\ten{-1}\pm1.3\ten{-5}\,GeV$
\end_inset

 (PDG for K neutral, which is the actual particle) and its mean lifetime
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\k}=8.9564\ten{-11}\pm3.3\ten{-14}\,s$
\end_inset

.
 The lifetime, 
\begin_inset Formula $c\tau_{\k}=2.6844\,cm$
\end_inset

 is of the same order as the spectrometer's resolution, meaning the particle
 decays along the path from the injection point to the E-Cal.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\k$
\end_inset

's two most common decay modes, which together occur 
\begin_inset Formula $99.9\%$
\end_inset

 of the time, are 
\begin_inset Formula $\k\rightarrow\p\p\,(30.7\%)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\k\rightarrow\pi^{+}\pi^{-}\,(69.2\%)$
\end_inset

 (PDG).
 This experiment will not consider any other decay modes.
 As was mentioned in the previous section, 
\begin_inset Formula $\p$
\end_inset

 decays instantaneously (when compared with the resolution of the spectrometer)
 via 
\begin_inset Formula $\p\rightarrow2\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Photons or 
\begin_inset Formula $\p$
\end_inset

 particles leave no trace in the spectrometer which renders locating the
 vertex of the decay impossible or nearly impossible.
 The vertex of the decay is necessary in the calculation of the lifetime,
 which, theortically, should be measurable using a different decay mode.
 If one looks at 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{\pm}$
\end_inset

 which have an elemetary charge corresponding to their sign and a lifetime
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $c\tau_{\pi^{\pm}}=7.8045\,m$
\end_inset

 (PDG) which is significantly greater than the length of the measurement
 apparatus, and so, it is assumed they do not decay.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{\pm}$
\end_inset

 are hadrons they do not deposit their entire energy inside the E-Cal and
 their momentum must be measured in some other way.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{\pm}$
\end_inset

 particles are charged and therefore have their trajectories curved by the
 magnetic field and leave a trace in the spectrometer.
 Using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "spectrometer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and the curvature outputted by the simulation, it is possible to measure
 the transverse momentum of each particle.
 Using conservation of 3-momentum, the angle between the particles at the
 decay vertex, and the position of the vertex, it is possible to calculate
 both the invariant mass and the lifetime of 
\begin_inset Formula $\k$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear then that this is the decay mode of interest.
 As with the previous section, some events make measurement impossible or
 incorrect, if produced by a bug in the simulation, thus, an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

interesting event
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 must be defined, all other events (excluding those which did not register
 in any detector) will be counted and promptly discarded.
 An 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

interesting event
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 will have 2-3 tracks (which are identified by the simulation), opposite
 curvatures in the chosen tracks (if there are 3) and the tracks must share
 a vertex.
 In case there are 3 tracks, the two tracks with the most hits are taken.
 In order to compare the branching ratio of the different decay modes to
 the theoretical value each event is classified into 
\begin_inset Formula $\k\to\p\p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\k\to\pi^{+}\pi^{-}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $BUG$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $BUG$
\end_inset

 is an event with more than 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 pulse-height clusters or with no interaction with the E-Cal and spectrometer.
 These events are discarded without being considered in the branching ratio,
 they account for 
\begin_inset Formula $26\%$
\end_inset

 of the events.
 As it is simpler to define what a 
\begin_inset Formula $\k\to\p\p$
\end_inset

 event registers, it is assumed that all events which are not a 
\begin_inset Formula $BUG$
\end_inset

 or a 
\begin_inset Formula $\k\to\p\p$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\k\to\pi^{+}\pi^{-}$
\end_inset

 events.
 And so, a 
\begin_inset Formula $\k\to\p\p$
\end_inset

 event is expected to have a pulse-height cluster(s) and no track.
 In the simulation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\k\to\p\p$
\end_inset

 account for 
\begin_inset Formula $77\%$
\end_inset

 of events (or 
\begin_inset Formula $57\%$
\end_inset

 if a 
\begin_inset Formula $BUG$
\end_inset

 event is not considered a 
\begin_inset Formula $\k\to\p\p$
\end_inset

 event but is counted), thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\k\to\pi^{+}\pi^{-}$
\end_inset

 account for 
\begin_inset Formula $23\%$
\end_inset

 of events.
 This finding contradicts the theortical branching ratios, which are the
 exact opposite in terms of decay mode prominance.
\end_layout

