\begin_layout Standard
The lifetime of 
\begin_inset Formula $\k$
\end_inset

 will be calculated using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lifetime calc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Each event has a measured invariant mass which will be used.
 The length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is calculated using the vertex's position after adding 
\begin_inset Formula $10\,cm$
\end_inset

 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 axis since the injection point is at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-10\,cm$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\sqrt{(x+10)^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 The momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 will be calculated using 3-momentum conservation in the lab's frame of
 reference.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 are the angles of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p_{\pi^{+}}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p_{\pi^{-}}}$
\end_inset

 relative to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}$
\end_inset

 respectively, then, using the angle of the vertex, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vp=\alpha+\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Using conservation of 3-momentum perpendicular to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}$
\end_inset

, one gets 
\begin_inset Formula $\abs{p_{\pi^{+}}}sin(\alpha)=\abs{p_{\pi^{-}}}sin(\beta)$
\end_inset

.
 By combining the two one gets 
\begin_inset Formula $tan(\beta)=\abs{p_{\pi^{+}}}sin(\vp)/(\abs{p_{\pi^{+}}}cos(\vp)+\abs{p_{\pi^{-}}})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\vp-\beta$
\end_inset

, both of which can be calculated using the measured momenta from invariant
 mass calculation.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is then 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\abs{p_{\pi^{+}}}cos(\alpha)+\abs{p_{\pi^{-}}}cos(\beta)$
\end_inset

.
 A histogram with 20 bins (including empty bins), each with width of 
\begin_inset Formula $1.3\ten{-9}\,s$
\end_inset

 was made.
 The average lifetime in each bin was then taken as the representing measurement
 of that bin.
 The number of events in each bin should distribute according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lifetime distribution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, an exponential fit of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Events_{\k}(\tau)=a_{0}e^{-\frac{\tau}{\tau_{0}}}+a_{2}\label{expo fit - kShort}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

was made, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the normalization factor and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{0},a_{2}$
\end_inset

 represent the invariant mass of 
\begin_inset Formula $\p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{0}^{\p}$
\end_inset

and the energy width, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 respectively.
